Also what is the switch detecting?</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2025-02-02T16:08:07.453Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":6,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":70,"readers_count":69,"score":14.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":484278,"topic_slug":"disable-limit-switch-on-rev-spark-flex","display_username":"icemannie","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":17898,"username":"burde1jb","name":"burde1jb","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/burde1jb/{size}/270229_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":28240,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/disable-limit-switch-on-rev-spark-flex/484278/7","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3500181,"name":"Dan","username":"tekdemo","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/tekdemo/{size}/138330_2.png","created_at":"2025-02-02T21:24:31.617Z","cooked":"<p>it sounds like you have a logic error in the code. If we simplify the &amp;&amp; logic a bit, this is what the bot is <em>actually</em> doing: Having one button turn the intake on, and one button turn the change the limit switch behavior.</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">if( controller2.getRightButton() ){
    intakeSubsystem.intakeOn(true);
}
else{
    intakeSubsystem.intakeOff();
}

if(controller2.getLeftBumperButton()){
    intakeSubsystem.limitSwitchOff(true);
} else {
    intakeSubsystem.limitSwitchOff(false);
}
</code></pre>
<p>What you described in words would look different when put into code. That would look like this:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">if (controller2.getLeftBumperButton() ){
    intakeSubsystem.intakeOn(true);
    intakeSubsystem.limitSwitchOff(true);    
}
else if(controller2.getRIghtBumperButton()){
    intakeSubsystem.intakeOn(true);
    intakeSubsystem.limitSwitchOff(false);
}
else{
    intakeSubsystem.intakeOff();
}
</code></pre>
<p>Note, that if the driver hits <em>both</em> left and right buttons at the same time, then it will run the first condition (the top one); In this case, that would halt the intake.</p>
<p>Another critical feature is that running motor configs commands (this guy: <code>intakeMotor.configure(...) </code>) is a <em>very</em> slow operation: The system will wait for ~20 ms for the motor to send a reply back, and confirm that the new configuration is set. This is about 50% of your robot’s general loop time, and when you do it <em>every</em> loop, you’ll get loop overruns and major code failures.<br>
Instead, you want to do two things:</p>
<ul>
<li>If you’re using Commands, put it in an <code>initialize()</code> call or decorator. This means you only do it when a button state changes.</li>
<li>use <code>intakeMotor.configureAsync(...)</code> ; This async version configures the motor, but does not wait for the motor to send back a reply. (or, in technical terms, it’s “non-blocking”, and asynchronous). This is much better for loops like this.</li>
</ul>","post_number":8,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2025-02-02T21:25:25.007Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":65,"readers_count":64,"score":18.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":484278,"topic_slug":"disable-limit-switch-on-rev-spark-flex","display_username":"Dan","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":44763,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"2811 Programming Mentor"},"post_url":"/t/disable-limit-switch-on-rev-spark-flex/484278/8","custom_user_title":"2811 Programming Mentor","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3500843,"name":"burde1jb","username":"burde1jb","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/burde1jb/{size}/270229_2.png","created_at":"2025-02-03T18:21:55.767Z","cooked":"<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="tekdemo" data-post="8" data-topic="484278">
